<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<appendix xml:id="appendix-solutions">
  <title>Selected Solutions</title>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-1-what-we-do-with-language">
    <title>Exercise Set 1: What We Do With Language</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Asking.</em> The speaker is requesting that someone send a file. Although phrased as a question ("Could you..."), its dominant function is a polite request for action, not a claim about how things are.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Promising.</em> The speaker is committing to a future action (bringing the handouts tomorrow). This is not asserting that something is the case; it is undertaking an obligation.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Performing.</em> This is a performative utterance. By saying "I hereby resign," the speaker performs the act of resigning. The sentence does not describe a resignation — it <em>is</em> one.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <em>Explaining.</em> The explanandum is "the room is cold" — an already-accepted fact. The explanans is "someone left the window open overnight." The speaker is giving the reason <em>why</em> the room is cold, not trying to convince someone that it is cold.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> <em>Stating.</em> The sentence asserts that something is the case (a claim about the age of a tree on campus). It is either true or false.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> <em>Promising.</em> The speaker is committing to a future action (picking someone up at seven). This is not a truth-apt assertion about how things are; it is an undertaking.</p>
    <p><term>13.</term> <em>Arguing.</em> The conclusion is "you should take the bus to campus." The premise is "parking costs twelve dollars a day." The indicator word <em>since</em> flags the premise.</p>
    <p><term>15.</term> <em>Expressing / Greeting.</em> This is a social expression of goodwill. It does not assert that something is the case and does not offer reasons for a claim.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-2-arguing-and-persuading">
    <title>Exercise Set 2: Arguing and Persuading</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Persuading without arguing.</em> The poster uses positive imagery (smiling students, trees) to create an emotional association with the university. No reasons are offered for why you should choose UMW. "Choose UMW" is a command paired with persuasive imagery, not an argument.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Persuading without arguing.</em> Repetition is a persuasion technique — it creates familiarity — but no premise or conclusion is offered. There is no reasoning, just a jingle played five times.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Neither.</em> This is a command. The coach is directing the players to repeat a drill. No claim is being supported by reasons, and no persuasion technique is being employed beyond the coach's authority.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <em>Both arguing and persuading.</em> The email gives a reason (the $50 surcharge) for a recommended action (register by Friday). The implicit conclusion is "you should register by Friday"; the premise is "registration after Friday incurs a $50 surcharge." It is also designed to motivate action through the concrete dollar amount.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> <em>Persuading without arguing.</em> The classmate is trying to get you to believe the professor is great but offers no reasons — only an appeal to trust ("Trust me"). There is no premise supporting the conclusion.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-3-statements-and-non-statements">
    <title>Exercise Set 3: Statements and Non-Statements</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts that the registrar's office opens at eight. This is either true or false.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Not a statement.</em> This is a command or request. It is not asserting that something is the case; it is asking someone to do something.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts a specific claim about the world (exactly 19 students were in this room at a particular time). It is either true or false, even though no one may have counted.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts that pineapple belongs on pizza. By the definition in Chapter 1, it is either true or false, regardless of how many people disagree. Someone tempted by the fact-vs-opinion taxonomy might call this "just an opinion," but the chapter's criterion is whether the sentence says that something is the case — and it does.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts something is the case — namely, that no one knows a particular piece of information. It is true or false. Note: this is a statement <em>about knowledge</em>, not about grains of sand.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts that wealth taxes are just. It is either true or false. Someone might call this "just an opinion," but disagreement and truth are different things.</p>
    <p><term>13.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts something about the speaker's mental state — that the speaker doubts it will rain. That assertion is either true or false (the speaker either does or does not have that doubt).</p>
    <p><term>15.</term> <em>Statement.</em> It asserts that climate change is the most urgent crisis of our time. It is either true or false. The fact that people disagree about its truth does not prevent it from being a statement.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-4-truth-knowledge-and-consensus">
    <title>Exercise Set 4: Truth, Knowledge, and Consensus</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Yes, it is a statement. The difficulty is mainly about <em>knowledge</em>: no one knows the exact number of stars in the Milky Way, so no one knows whether the number is even or odd. But there is a definite number, and that number is either even or odd. The sentence is true or false regardless of our ignorance.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Yes, it is a statement. The difficulty is mainly about <em>consensus</em>: people disagree about what the best grading system is. But the sentence asserts that something is the case, and it is either true or false. Disagreement does not settle whether a sentence is a statement.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Yes, it is a statement. The difficulty is <em>neither</em> — there is no knowledge gap and no serious disagreement. Truth, knowledge, and consensus all align here. It is still a statement for the same reason the harder cases are: it asserts that something is the case.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Yes, it is a statement. The difficulty is mainly about <em>consensus</em> (and perhaps partly about <em>knowledge</em>, since the effects of abolishing tests are uncertain). People disagree strongly. But the sentence asserts that something is the case, and it is either true or false. The disagreement is about <em>what is true</em>, not about whether the sentence has a truth value.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> Yes, it is a statement. The difficulty is mainly about <em>knowledge</em>: no one is likely to have observed the exact time the painting was hung. But the world was arranged in some definite way at that time, and the sentence either correctly describes it or not.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> Yes, it is a statement. The difficulty is mainly about <em>consensus</em>: this is a deeply contested moral claim. But by the chapter's criterion, it asserts that something is the case (that eating animals is wrong), and it is either true or false.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-5-fact-opinion-and-statementhood">
    <title>Exercise Set 5: Fact, Opinion, and Statementhood</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> The classification is wrong. "Factory farming is wrong" asserts that something is the case — that factory farming is wrong. By the chapter's definition, it is a statement with a truth value. Calling it "an opinion" describes whose belief it is, not what kind of sentence it is. A sentence can be both someone's opinion (a belief they hold) and a statement (a sentence that is true or false). The categories collapse into each other.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> This confuses consensus with truth. People disagree about many things that are true or false. Disagreement tells you that the question is unresolved <em>among people</em>, not that the sentence lacks a truth value. The sentence asserts that something is the case; it is either true or false regardless of whether anyone has settled the debate.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> This confuses <em>provability</em> with <em>statementhood</em>. Both sentences assert that something is the case. Both are either true or false. The fact that one is easy to verify and the other is not does not change what kind of sentence each is. The chapter's criterion is whether the sentence says that something is the case, not whether we can prove it.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> This is wrong on two counts. First, "we should raise the minimum wage" is a statement — it asserts that something is the case, and it is either true or false. Second, even if one insists on calling it "an opinion," opinions can serve as premises. Arguments are built out of statements, and the chapter shows that contested claims are still statements. The fact-vs-opinion taxonomy does not determine what can function as a premise.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> This assumes that "matters of taste" are not truth-apt. But "pineapple belongs on pizza" asserts that something is the case. By the chapter's definition and the working assumption of classical logic, assertoric sentences are either true or false. The sentence says that something is the case; it is a statement.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-6-premises-conclusions-and-indicators">
    <title>Exercise Set 6: Premises, Conclusions, and Indicators</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Conclusion: We need to send the file electronically. Premises: P1: The printer is out of toner. P2: The handout is due in ten minutes. Indicator: <em>Since</em> (premise indicator).</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The printer is out of toner.</p>
    <p>P2: The handout is due in ten minutes.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: We need to send the file electronically.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Conclusion: We should not rely on the app's arrival time estimate. Premise: The app's arrival time estimate has been wrong three times this week. Indicator: <em>because</em> (premise indicator).</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The app's arrival time estimate has been wrong three times this week.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: We should not rely on the app's arrival time estimate.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Conclusion: The department should hire another advisor. Premises: P1: Either the department hires another advisor or students will keep waiting weeks for appointments. P2: Students should not have to wait weeks for appointments. Indicator: <em>So</em> (conclusion indicator).</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Either the department hires another advisor or students will keep waiting weeks for appointments.</p>
    <p>P2: Students should not have to wait weeks for appointments.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The department should hire another advisor.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Conclusion: The museum should extend its hours on weekends. Premises: P1: Families with school-age children can only visit on Saturdays and Sundays. P2: The museum currently closes at three, which is too early for most families. Indicator: None explicit. The conclusion is the first sentence; the rest are reasons.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Families with school-age children can only visit on Saturdays and Sundays.</p>
    <p>P2: The museum currently closes at three, which is too early for most families.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The museum should extend its hours on weekends.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> Conclusion: More students will take on debt. Premises: P1: If tuition increases, then more students will take on debt. P2: Tuition is increasing. Indicator: <em>Therefore</em> (conclusion indicator).</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If tuition increases, then more students will take on debt.</p>
    <p>P2: Tuition is increasing.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: More students will take on debt.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> Conclusion: We cannot trust the poll results. Premises: P1: The sample was not random. P2: Fewer than 200 people responded. Indicator: <em>since</em> (premise indicator).</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The sample was not random.</p>
    <p>P2: Fewer than 200 people responded.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: We cannot trust the poll results.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-7-standard-form-without-indicator-words">
    <title>Exercise Set 7: Standard Form Without Indicator Words</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Conclusion: I am not signing up for the 8 a.m. section. (This is the claim being defended; the other sentences are offered as reasons.)</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: My shift ends at midnight on Tuesdays.</p>
    <p>P2: I never sleep well after closing.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: I am not signing up for the 8 a.m. section.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Conclusion: That road will flood again this spring. (The claim the speaker is asking the listener to accept.)</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The drainage ditch is still blocked.</p>
    <p>P2: Every heavy rain last year covered the intersection.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: That road will flood again this spring.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Conclusion: We should take the train to D.C. (The recommendation being supported.)</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Parking downtown is expensive.</p>
    <p>P2: The station is only a ten-minute walk from the museum.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: We should take the train to D.C.</p>
    <p>How the conclusion was recognized: The first sentence is the recommendation — it is the claim the speaker wants the listener to accept. The remaining sentences are factual claims offered as reasons for it.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Conclusion: The scholarship deadline should be extended.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The financial aid office did not send the announcement until three days before it was due.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The scholarship deadline should be extended.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> Conclusion: The student government should publish its meeting minutes online.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Currently, only people who attend the meetings know what was discussed.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The student government should publish its meeting minutes online.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-8-conditional-sentences">
    <title>Exercise Set 8: Conditional Sentences</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Antecedent: It rains. Consequent: The sidewalks will be wet.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Antecedent: The argument is sound. Consequent: It is valid.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Antecedent: The grant is approved. Consequent: The lab will replace its oldest equipment.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Antecedent: The premise is false. Consequent: The argument is not sound.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> Antecedent: The experiment is not replicated. Consequent: The results should be treated with caution.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> Antecedent: The bridge is closed. Consequent: Commuters will need an alternate route.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-9-modus-ponens-and-modus-tollens">
    <title>Exercise Set 9: Modus Ponens and Modus Tollens</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the alarm is armed, then opening the door will trigger it.</p>
    <p>P2: The alarm is armed.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Opening the door will trigger it.</p>
    <p>Form: <term>Modus ponens.</term> The second premise affirms the antecedent ("the alarm is armed"), and the conclusion affirms the consequent ("opening the door will trigger it"). Antecedent: The alarm is armed. Consequent: Opening the door will trigger it.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the sculpture were made of bronze, then it would not be attracted to a magnet.</p>
    <p>P2: The sculpture is attracted to a magnet.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The sculpture is not made of bronze.</p>
    <p>Form: <term>Modus tollens.</term> The second premise denies the consequent ("would not be attracted" is denied by "is attracted"), and the conclusion denies the antecedent. Antecedent: The sculpture were made of bronze. Consequent: It would not be attracted to a magnet.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the course required a textbook, it would appear on the bookstore list.</p>
    <p>P2: The course does not require a textbook.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: It does not appear on the bookstore list.</p>
    <p>Form: <term>Neither.</term> This argument denies the antecedent, which is a formal fallacy. Modus tollens denies the <em>consequent</em>, while modus ponens affirms the <em>antecedent</em>. (The course might appear on the bookstore list for some other reason.) Antecedent: The course required a textbook. Consequent: It would appear on the bookstore list.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If class is canceled, then the assignment deadline will be extended.</p>
    <p>P2: Class is canceled.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The assignment deadline will be extended.</p>
    <p>Form: <term>Modus ponens.</term> The second premise affirms the antecedent. Antecedent: Class is canceled. Consequent: The assignment deadline will be extended.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the study abroad program requires a 3.0 GPA, then students below 3.0 are ineligible.</p>
    <p>P2: The program requires a 3.0 GPA.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Students below 3.0 are ineligible.</p>
    <p>Form: <term>Modus ponens.</term> The second premise affirms the antecedent. Antecedent: The study abroad program requires a 3.0 GPA. Consequent: Students below 3.0 are ineligible.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-10-argument-or-explanation">
    <title>Exercise Set 10: Argument or Explanation?</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Explanation.</em> The explanandum is "the coffee tastes bitter" — this is already observed and accepted. The explanans is "the grounds were over-extracted" — the reason <em>why</em> the coffee tastes bitter.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Argument.</em> The conclusion is "you should bring an umbrella" — a recommendation the speaker is trying to get the listener to accept. The premise is "the forecast calls for thunderstorms."</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Argument.</em> The conclusion is "we should leave the building" — the recommended action. The premise is "the fire alarm is going off." The speaker is reasoning forward from a current observation to a course of action; the action is in question, not the fact of the alarm.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <em>Argument.</em> The conclusion is "you should use a computer lab machine for the assignment." The premise is "this laptop cannot run the required software." The indicator word <em>since</em> flags the premise. The speaker is reasoning toward a recommendation, not explaining an already-accepted fact.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> <em>Explanation.</em> The explanandum is "the Wi-Fi is slow" — already observed and accepted. The explanans is "too many devices are connected to the network" — the cause.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> <em>Explanation.</em> The explanandum is "the pipes froze" — already observed. The explanans is "the thermostat was set too low overnight" — the cause. The speaker is explaining why a known event occurred, not trying to convince anyone that it occurred.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-11-extracting-arguments-from-realistic-prose">
    <title>Exercise Set 11: Extracting Arguments From Realistic Prose</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Conclusion: Students should visit office hours early in the semester.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Early visits make it easier to ask for help later.</p>
    <p>P2: Early visits give professors a better sense of what students are finding confusing.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Students should visit office hours early in the semester.</p>
    <p>Note: The first sentence ("Most students think office hours are only for emergencies, but that is a mistake") is orientation — it sets up what the argument pushes back against but is not itself a premise of the inference.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Conclusion: We should replace the old projector in Monroe Hall.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The projector cuts out during class.</p>
    <p>P2: Replacement bulbs are no longer easy to order.</p>
    <p>P3: Several instructors have stopped using media clips because they cannot trust the equipment.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: We should replace the old projector in Monroe Hall.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Conclusion: The committee should not postpone the vote again.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Everyone has had the proposal for three weeks.</p>
    <p>P2: The remaining objections are about implementation details, not about the main principle.</p>
    <p>P3: Implementation details can be handled after approval.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The committee should not postpone the vote again.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Conclusion: College athletes should be allowed to profit from their name, image, and likeness.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: College athletes generate millions in revenue for their schools.</p>
    <p>P2: Other students are free to earn money from their talents.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: College athletes should be allowed to profit from their name, image, and likeness.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> Conclusion: Standardized test scores should be optional in admissions.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Scores correlate more strongly with family income than with college performance.</p>
    <p>P2: Many high-performing students test poorly due to anxiety.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Standardized test scores should be optional in admissions.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-12-layered-arguments-and-sub-conclusions">
    <title>Exercise Set 12: Layered Arguments and Sub-Conclusions</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Many students who need tutoring work during the day.</p>
    <p>P2: Students who work during the day cannot attend most current tutoring sessions.</p>
    <p>C1: The current schedule excludes many of the students who need help. <em>(from P1 and P2)</em></p>
    <p>P3: Expanding evening tutoring would make academic support available to more students.</p>
    <p>Therefore C2: The university should expand evening tutoring. <em>(from C1 and P3)</em></p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Drivers often fail to see pedestrians at the crosswalk at night.</p>
    <p>P2: Poor visibility makes collisions more likely.</p>
    <p>C1: The crosswalk is dangerous at night. <em>(from P1 and P2)</em></p>
    <p>P3: Better lighting would improve visibility.</p>
    <p>P4: Improving visibility would make the crosswalk safer.</p>
    <p>Therefore C2: The city should install better lighting near the crosswalk. <em>(from C1, P3, and P4)</em></p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The software collects sensitive data.</p>
    <p>P2: Sensitive data can be misused or exposed in a breach.</p>
    <p>C1: The software creates serious privacy risks. <em>(from P1 and P2)</em></p>
    <p>P3: Tools that create serious privacy risks should be avoided unless they are necessary.</p>
    <p>P4: Professors can take attendance without location tracking.</p>
    <p>C2: This software is not necessary. <em>(from P4)</em></p>
    <p>Therefore C3: We should not use attendance software that tracks students' locations. <em>(from C1, P3, and C2)</em></p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Students arrive with widely varying reasoning skills.</p>
    <p>P2: A shared course would give everyone a common vocabulary for evaluating arguments.</p>
    <p>C1: A common vocabulary makes class discussions in other courses more productive. <em>(from P2)</em></p>
    <p>P3: More productive discussions improve learning across the curriculum.</p>
    <p>Therefore C2: We should require all first-year students to take a critical thinking course. <em>(from P1, C1, and P3)</em></p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-13-mixed-review">
    <title>Exercise Set 13: Mixed Review</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Argument.</em> Contains a conditional: antecedent = "the storm reaches campus before noon"; consequent = "afternoon labs should be canceled." The argument affirms the antecedent (the storm is projected to arrive by 11:30, which is before noon). Indicator: <em>so</em>.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the storm reaches campus before noon, then afternoon labs should be canceled.</p>
    <p>P2: The storm is projected to arrive by 11:30.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Afternoon labs should be canceled.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Not a statement and not an argument.</em> This is a command/request. It is not asserting that something is the case and not offering reasons for a claim.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Argument.</em> Contains a conditional: antecedent = "the collaboration policy applies to group chat notes"; consequent = "students must list those notes in their acknowledgments." The argument affirms the antecedent (modus ponens). Indicator: <em>Therefore</em>.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the collaboration policy applies to group chat notes, then students must list those notes in their acknowledgments.</p>
    <p>P2: The collaboration policy does apply to group chat notes.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Students must list those notes in their acknowledgments.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <em>Explanation plus a statement.</em> The first sentence is an explanation: the explanandum is "the classroom was moved" (already known); the explanans is "the projector broke." The second sentence ("The new classroom is in Combs") is a separate statement providing information. Neither sentence is part of an argument.</p>
    <p><term>9.</term> <em>Argument.</em> Contains a conditional: antecedent = "the committee meets on Friday"; consequent = "the proposal will be voted on before the deadline." The argument denies the consequent (modus tollens). Indicator: <em>Therefore</em>.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: If the committee meets on Friday, then the proposal will be voted on before the deadline.</p>
    <p>P2: The proposal will not be voted on before the deadline.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: The committee is not meeting on Friday.</p>
    <p><term>11.</term> <em>Argument.</em> Conclusion: You should apply for the internship. No indicator words. The conclusion is the recommendation (the claim the speaker wants the listener to accept).</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: The application deadline is next week.</p>
    <p>P2: The position pays well.</p>
    <p>P3: The position is directly related to your major.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: You should apply for the internship.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sol-exercise-set-14-short-writing-prompts">
    <title>Exercise Set 14: Short Writing Prompts</title>
    <p>No solutions provided. These are open-ended writing prompts; responses will vary by student.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch2-exercise-set-7-revisiting-ch1-reconstruction">
    <title>Chapter 2, Exercise Set 7: Revisiting a Chapter 1 Reconstruction</title>
    <p>A model answer follows. Other defensible answers are possible; the goal is to apply the tools of Chapter 2 to the original reconstruction with care.</p>

    <p><term>(a)</term> <em>Dependent / independent labels.</em></p>
    <p>C1 (from P2 alone). Only one premise is offered at this step, so there is no dependence question to ask.</p>
    <p>C2 (from P1 and C1, dependent). P1 alone tells us about cost efficiency; C1 alone tells us what the aid does. Neither alone supports the broader claim that Oxfam efficiently uses contributions to help end long-term poverty by providing the tools for people to get an education and support their families. Together they do.</p>
    <p>C3 (from C2, P3, and an implicit premise — see (b); dependent). The structure of the inference is that Oxfam's efficient use of donations <em>plus</em> the goodness of helping <em>plus</em> a connecting principle is what licenses the recommendation. Removing any one piece weakens the support significantly.</p>

    <p><term>(b)</term> <em>An implicit premise.</em></p>
    <p>The natural implicit premise is something like: <q>You should donate to programs that efficiently end long-term poverty and that you find rewarding to support.</q> A more minimal version: <q>You should donate to programs that meet conditions like efficiency and that produce satisfaction in the donor.</q> Without an implicit principle of this kind, the move from C2 and P3 to C3 isn't licensed; the reconstruction needs the bridging claim. Adding it as P4 (implicit) makes the inference to C3 explicit.</p>

    <p><term>(c)</term> <em>Background, rhetorical, or emotional work.</em></p>
    <p>P3 (<q>It feels good to help people</q>) is doing different work from the other premises. The earlier premises and C1 and C2 build a case about Oxfam's effectiveness. P3 shifts to an emotional appeal. A charitable reconstruction can keep it as a premise — donor satisfaction is one reason to give, and the original passage offers it as one — but a more critical reconstruction might flag it as rhetorical, particularly because the case for donating goes through even without it. Reasonable reconstructions can disagree here. Either choice is defensible; what matters is making the choice consciously and being able to explain it.</p>

    <p><term>(d)</term> <em>What Chapter 2's tools added.</em></p>
    <p>The Chapter 1 reconstruction identified the structure of the argument but did not say <em>how</em> the support worked at each step. Chapter 2's tools added three things: explicit dependent/independent labels showing which premises rely on which others; an implicit premise that makes the move to the conclusion licensed rather than left for the reader to supply silently; and a finer reading of what each sentence in the original passage is doing — premise, sub-conclusion, or rhetorical addition. The reconstruction is the same in outline but more rigorous about the relations between the parts.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch3-exercise-set-1-identifying-valid-forms">
    <title>Chapter 3, Exercise Set 1: Identifying Valid Forms</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Modus ponens.</em> The first premise has the form <q>If P, then Q</q>; the second premise affirms P; the conclusion affirms Q.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Disjunctive syllogism.</em> The first premise gives an either/or: either the data center applies for a new permit or construction stops. The second premise denies the first disjunct, so the conclusion affirms the other disjunct.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch3-exercise-set-2-spotting-invalid-forms">
    <title>Chapter 3, Exercise Set 2: Spotting Invalid Forms</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Affirming the consequent.</em> The argument says: if a senator is corrupt, then they accept dark-money donations; Senator X accepts dark-money donations; therefore Senator X is corrupt. Accepting such donations is treated as if it proves the antecedent, but the conditional does not say that only corrupt senators accept such donations.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Affirming the consequent.</em> The argument says: if a country has a stable currency, foreign investment increases; foreign investment increased; therefore the country has a stable currency. The increase in investment could have another cause.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch3-exercise-set-3-constructing-counterexamples">
    <title>Chapter 3, Exercise Set 3: Constructing Counterexamples</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> One counterexample: If something is a dog, then it is a mammal. This animal is a mammal. Therefore this animal is a dog. The premises can both be true while the conclusion is false, since the animal might be a cat. That shows affirming the consequent is invalid.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> One counterexample: All dogs are mammals. All mammals are animals. Therefore all animals are dogs. The premises are true, but the conclusion is false. The form moves in the wrong direction at the last step.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch3-exercise-set-4-validity-soundness-or-neither">
    <title>Chapter 3, Exercise Set 4: Validity, Soundness, or Neither</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Valid and sound.</em> The argument is an instance of modus ponens. The premises are true: two plus two equals four, and if that is true, arithmetic works as we have learned it.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Valid and sound.</em> The argument is an instance of modus ponens. The moon does orbit the Earth, and the conditional connecting that fact to the existence of tides is true enough for the purposes of the example.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch3-exercise-set-5-strength-and-cogency">
    <title>Chapter 3, Exercise Set 5: Strength and Cogency</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Strong; probably cogent if the statistic is accurate.</em> Ninety-three out of one hundred past winters is a substantial pattern, so the premise gives strong inductive support. Cogency depends on whether the historical claim is true and relevant to the coming winter.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Strong; cogent if the survey information is true.</em> The argument cites a large percentage and says the survey went to a representative sample. If those claims are true, the argument is a good inductive argument for the conclusion that the ordinance probably increases costs for small businesses generally.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch3-exercise-set-6-mixed-evaluation">
    <title>Chapter 3, Exercise Set 6: Mixed Evaluation</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Deductive.</em> The argument is modus ponens: if the city raises the property tax rate, then school revenue will increase; the city did raise the rate; therefore school revenue will increase. It is valid. Soundness depends on whether both premises are true, especially the conditional about revenue.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Deductive.</em> The argument is disjunctive syllogism: either the proposal cleared committee or the chair tabled it; it did not clear committee; therefore the chair tabled it. It is valid. It is sound if the either/or premise and the denial of the first disjunct are true.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch4-exercise-set-1-identifying-vague-terms">
    <title>Chapter 4, Exercise Set 1: Identifying Vague Terms</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Wealthy</em> is vague. There are clear cases of wealthy and clear cases of not wealthy, but there are borderline households where the classification is unclear. If the sentence is used to defend the policy, the vagueness matters because the audience needs to know who is actually affected.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Natural</em> is vague. It may mean not synthetic, minimally processed, plant-derived, non-artificial, or something else. In product marketing, that vagueness can do argumentative work by making the product sound healthier or safer without saying exactly what property it has.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch4-exercise-set-2-ambiguity">
    <title>Chapter 4, Exercise Set 2: Ambiguity</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Ambiguous; lexical.</em> <q>Bank</q> can mean a financial institution or the side of a river. The sentence does not tell us which meaning is intended.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Ambiguous; syntactic.</em> It can mean that the chicken is prepared and ready for someone to eat, or that the chicken itself is ready to eat some food. The grammar allows both readings.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch4-exercise-set-3-spotting-equivocation">
    <title>Chapter 4, Exercise Set 3: Spotting Equivocation</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> The argument equivocates on <q>end.</q> In the first premise, <q>end of life</q> means the termination of life. In the second premise, <q>end</q> means aim, purpose, or goal. The inference fails because death is being substituted for purpose by using the same word in two different senses.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> The argument equivocates on <q>law.</q> In <q>all laws can be broken,</q> the word means human rules or legal requirements. In <q>law of gravity,</q> it means a scientific regularity. The inference fails because a law of nature is not the same kind of thing as a rule one can violate.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch4-exercise-set-4-classifying-definitions">
    <title>Chapter 4, Exercise Set 4: Classifying Definitions</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Stipulative definition.</em> The phrase <q>for the purposes of this study</q> signals that the author is assigning a precise meaning for a specific context.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Persuasive definition.</em> The definition builds approval of <q>traditional values</q> and disapproval of <q>government bureaucrats</q> into the meaning of <q>true freedom.</q> It is trying to steer evaluation, not just report usage.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch4-exercise-set-5-critiquing-definitions">
    <title>Chapter 4, Exercise Set 5: Critiquing Definitions</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> The definition is circular. Defining <q>logic</q> as the study of reasoning <q>logically</q> uses a close relative of the term being defined, so it does not explain the concept to someone who does not already understand it.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> The definition is too broad and too narrow, and partly negative. Many four-legged carnivorous mammals that are not dogs are not cats. It also risks excluding cats that do not have four legs. Saying <q>not a dog</q> does not identify what makes something a cat.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch4-exercise-set-6-mixed-application">
    <title>Chapter 4, Exercise Set 6: Mixed Application</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> The passage uses a persuasive definition of <q>real environmentalist.</q> It builds support for nuclear power into the meaning of the term, then uses that loaded definition to exclude Senator X. The language problem matters because the conclusion follows only if we accept the author's controversial definition.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> The passage relies on a problematic definition of <q>healthy foods</q> as foods without artificial ingredients. That definition is too broad: organic candy may lack artificial ingredients and still be unhealthy in ordinary nutritional terms. The argument's conclusion depends on that questionable definition.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch5-exercise-set-1-fallacies-of-relevance">
    <title>Chapter 5, Exercise Set 1: Identifying Fallacies of Relevance</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Ad hominem.</em> The response attacks Senator Carter's personal behavior rather than addressing the merits of her argument about climate policy. Her driving an SUV may raise a charge of inconsistency, but it does not by itself show that her policy argument is false.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Appeal to emotion.</em> The argument relies on fear about children growing up in an unrecognizable country rather than giving concrete reasons for the bill. Emotional concern may be relevant, but here it substitutes for evidence.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Red herring.</em> The reporter asks about a possible ethics violation. The senator shifts to the previous administration's fiscal record, which may matter politically but does not answer the question asked.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch5-exercise-set-2-weak-inductive-support">
    <title>Chapter 5, Exercise Set 2: Identifying Fallacies of Weak Inductive Support</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Hasty generalization.</em> Two layoffs are too small a sample to support a sweeping claim that the entire data center industry is collapsing.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Slippery slope.</em> The argument moves from background checks to registry, licensing, and confiscation without showing that each step is likely or that the first step would make the later steps unavoidable.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Rigid application of a generalization.</em> Even if most members of Congress usually follow constituent preferences, that generalization does not justify dismissing a specific contrary vote without looking at the evidence. The argument treats a broad pattern as if it settles every individual case.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch5-exercise-set-3-fallacies-of-presumption">
    <title>Chapter 5, Exercise Set 3: Identifying Fallacies of Presumption</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>False dichotomy.</em> The argument presents only two options: secure the borders or accept lawlessness. It ignores other possible positions, such as changing enforcement policy without accepting lawlessness.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Begging the question.</em> The argument assumes what it needs to prove. Calling the party <q>the party of working people</q> already builds in the conclusion that it supports working people.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch5-exercise-set-4-mixed-identification">
    <title>Chapter 5, Exercise Set 4: Mixed Identification</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Equivocation.</em> <q>Free speech</q> shifts between a constitutional right against government restriction and a broader cultural value about open expression. The constitutional conclusion does not follow from the broader use of the term.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Appeal to illegitimate authority, or at least weak appeal to authority.</em> Generals and security experts may be relevant authorities, but the argument gives no actual evidence for the necessity of the strikes and treats membership in the administration as enough to settle the matter.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Weak appeal to authority / suppressed evidence.</em> The fact that some supporters have run small businesses is not enough to show the bill will not hurt small businesses. The argument ignores the opponents' specific concern rather than answering it.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch5-exercise-set-5-legitimate-or-fallacious">
    <title>Chapter 5, Exercise Set 5: Legitimate or Fallacious?</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Legitimate appeal to authority.</em> The CDC is an appropriate expert source on vaccination rates and herd immunity. If the report is accurately represented, the conclusion about likely outbreaks is a reasonable expert-based inference, not a fallacious appeal to authority.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Legitimate cousin of ad hominem.</em> The point is not merely that Senator Lewis has a bad relative. The family financial connection is relevant to whether she had a conflict of interest and should have recused herself.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch5-exercise-set-6-construct-your-own">
    <title>Chapter 5, Exercise Set 6: Construct Your Own</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Model answer for <em>straw person</em>: <q>My opponent wants to review police funding priorities, which means she wants to abolish public safety. We should reject her proposal.</q> Diagnosis: the argument replaces a more modest proposal with an exaggerated version that is easier to attack.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Model answer for <em>slippery slope</em>: <q>If the city allows one supervised homeless shelter downtown, businesses will leave, tourism will collapse, and the whole downtown will fail. So we must reject the shelter.</q> Diagnosis: the argument predicts a chain of increasingly severe consequences without showing that the chain is likely.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch6-exercise-set-1-identifying-the-form">
    <title>Chapter 6, Exercise Set 1: Identifying the Form</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>A proposition.</em> It has the form <q>All S are P.</q></p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>E proposition.</em> It has the form <q>No S are P.</q></p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>A proposition.</em> It has the form <q>All S are P.</q></p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch6-exercise-set-2-translation-into-standard-form">
    <title>Chapter 6, Exercise Set 2: Translation into Standard Form</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <q>All senators are people who voted on the bill.</q> Form: A.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <q>Some data center proposals are not proposals approved by the county.</q> Form: O. <q>Not all</q> translates as <q>some are not.</q></p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <q>Some voters are voters who voted for the third-party candidate.</q> Form: I.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <q>No spiders are insects.</q> Form: E.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch6-exercise-set-3-drawing-the-diagram">
    <title>Chapter 6, Exercise Set 3: Drawing the Diagram</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> This is an A proposition: all registered voters are people eligible to vote in this election. Shade area 1, the S-only region. That marks the region of registered voters who are not eligible voters as empty.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> This is an I proposition: some tariffs are tariffs that have produced retaliatory measures. Place an X in area 2, the overlap between S and P.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch6-exercise-set-4-immediate-inferences-via-contradiction">
    <title>Chapter 6, Exercise Set 4: Immediate Inferences via Contradiction</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Valid.</em> <q>It is not the case that all dumpster fires are bad things</q> is the denial of an A proposition. Its contradictory is the O proposition: <q>Some dumpster fires are not bad things.</q></p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Invalid on the modern interpretation.</em> From <q>All bitcoin maximalists are speculators</q> it does not follow that some bitcoin maximalists exist. The conclusion is an I proposition, not the contradictory of the premise.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch6-exercise-set-5-conversion-obversion-contraposition">
    <title>Chapter 6, Exercise Set 5: Conversion, Obversion, Contraposition</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Contraposition; invalid.</em> The premise is an E proposition, and the conclusion is its contrapositive. On the modern interpretation, contraposition is valid for A and O propositions, but not for E propositions.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Obversion; valid.</em> <q>All crayons are non-toxic things</q> obverts to <q>No crayons are toxic things.</q> Obversion is valid for all four categorical forms.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Obversion; valid.</em> <q>Some Kyrie Irving fans are not Dallas Mavericks fans</q> obverts to <q>Some Kyrie Irving fans are non-Dallas-Mavericks-fans.</q> Obversion is valid for O propositions.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch6-exercise-set-6-complex-translations">
    <title>Chapter 6, Exercise Set 6: Complex Translations</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <q>All days identical to today are Mondays.</q> Form: A. This treats <q>today</q> as a one-member subject class.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <q>All people who can vote in this election are registered voters.</q> Form: A. <q>Only registered voters can vote</q> reverses the surface order.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <q>All true Americans are Trump supporters.</q> Form: A. <q>Only Trump supporters are true Americans</q> means that anyone in the true-American class is in the Trump-supporter class.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <q>All people identical to Hillary Clinton are people who should have been President of the United States.</q> Form: A. This is a singular statement translated by treating the named individual as a one-member class.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch7-exercise-set-1-terms-and-standard-form">
    <title>Chapter 7, Exercise Set 1: Terms and Standard Form</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> S = campaign surrogates; P = people who ask inconvenient questions; M = journalists.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: All journalists are people who ask inconvenient questions.</p>
    <p>P2: No campaign surrogates are journalists.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: No campaign surrogates are people who ask inconvenient questions.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> S = online investment schemes; P = transparent business practices; M = successful scams.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: No successful scams are transparent business practices.</p>
    <p>P2: Some online investment schemes are successful scams.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Some online investment schemes are not transparent business practices.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch7-exercise-set-2-venn-diagram-validity">
    <title>Chapter 7, Exercise Set 2: Venn-Diagram Validity</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Valid.</em> S = Americans; P = right-wing hate mongers; M = socialists. The first premise shades the P-and-M overlap. The second premise places an X in S-and-M. Since the P-and-M overlap is shaded, the X must be in S and M but outside P. That is enough for the O conclusion: some Americans are not right-wing hate mongers.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-sol-ch7-s02-01-premise">
      <caption>Premise diagram for Exercise Set 2, problem 1: areas 6 and 7 are shaded, and the X is forced into area 5.</caption>
      <image xml:id="image-sol-ch7-s02-01-premise" width="45%">
        <description>
          <p>
            A three-circle Venn diagram with S at bottom-left, P at
            bottom-right, and M at top. S represents Americans, P
            represents right-wing hate mongers, and M represents
            socialists. Areas 6 and 7, the overlap of P and M, are
            shaded. An X appears in area 5, the part of S and M
            outside P. This shows that some S are not P.
          </p>
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
            \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
            \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
            \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
            \begin{scope}
              \clip \Pright;
              \clip \Mtop;
              \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
            \end{scope}
            \draw \Sleft;
            \draw \Pright;
            \draw \Mtop;
            \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
            \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
            \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
            \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
            \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
            \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
            \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
            \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
            \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
            \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
            \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \node at (-0.65,0.65) {$\times$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Invalid.</em> S = widely read books; P = Kilgore Trout stories; M = works of neglected genius. The particular premise says that some works of neglected genius are not widely read books, which places an X outside S. The conclusion needs an X inside S and outside P. The premise diagram does not supply that.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-sol-ch7-s02-03-premise">
      <caption>Premise diagram for Exercise Set 2, problem 3: areas 2 and 3 are shaded, and the X is only somewhere in M outside S.</caption>
      <image xml:id="image-sol-ch7-s02-03-premise" width="45%">
        <description>
          <p>
            A three-circle Venn diagram with S at bottom-left, P at
            bottom-right, and M at top. S represents widely read
            books, P represents Kilgore Trout stories, and M
            represents works of neglected genius. Areas 2 and 3,
            the part of P outside M, are shaded. An X lies on the
            boundary between areas 7 and 8, showing that something
            is in M and outside S, but not showing whether it is in
            P. There is no X in area 1 or area 5, so the conclusion
            is not shown.
          </p>
        </description>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]
            \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
            \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
            \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
            \begin{scope}
              \clip \Pright;
              \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \fill[white] \Mtop;
            \end{scope}
            \draw \Sleft;
            \draw \Pright;
            \draw \Mtop;
            \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
            \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
            \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
            \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
            \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
            \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
            \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
            \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
            \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
            \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
            \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \node at (0.55,0.9) {$\times$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Valid.</em> S = students; P = people who notice hidden assumptions; M = people who read carefully. The particular premise places an X in S-and-M. The universal premise forces the M part outside P to be empty, so the X must also be in P. The conclusion's I claim follows.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-sol-ch7-s02-05-premise">
      <caption>Premise diagram for Exercise Set 2, problem 5: areas 5 and 8 are shaded, and the X is forced into area 6.</caption>
      <image xml:id="image-sol-ch7-s02-05-premise" width="45%">
        <description>
          <p>
            A three-circle Venn diagram with S at bottom-left, P at
