  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch7-exercise-set-3-mood-and-figure">
    <title>Chapter 7, Exercise Set 3: Mood and Figure</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> EAE-1. The major premise is M-P and the minor premise is S-M, so this is Figure 1. EAE-1 appears in the modern-valid form table, so the syllogism is valid.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> AAI-3. Both premises have M as subject, so this is Figure 3. AAI-3 does not appear in the modern-valid form table, so the syllogism is invalid on the modern interpretation. It tries to get a particular conclusion from universal premises without an existence claim.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> EIO-2. The major premise is P-M and the minor premise is S-M, so this is Figure 2. EIO-2 appears in the modern-valid form table, so the syllogism is valid.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch7-exercise-set-4-putting-prose-into-syllogism-form">
    <title>Chapter 7, Exercise Set 4: Putting Prose into Syllogism Form</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: All people who believe that technology can solve all moral problems are overly optimistic people.</p>
    <p>P2: Some futurists are people who believe that technology can solve all moral problems.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Some futurists are overly optimistic people.</p>
    <p>This is AII-1, so it is valid.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: All people who miss important context are poorly informed people.</p>
    <p>P2: All people who get their news only from social media are people who miss important context.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: All people who get their news only from social media are poorly informed people.</p>
    <p>This is AAA-1, so it is valid.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: All laws that degrade human personality are unjust laws.</p>
    <p>P2: All segregation statutes are laws that degrade human personality.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: All segregation statutes are unjust laws.</p>
    <p>This is AAA-1, so it is valid. A negative reconstruction is also acceptable: no laws that degrade human personality are just laws; all segregation statutes are laws that degrade human personality; therefore no segregation statutes are just laws. That version is EAE-1 and is also valid.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch7-exercise-set-5-explaining-invalidity">
    <title>Chapter 7, Exercise Set 5: Explaining Invalidity</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Invalid.</em> This has two negative premises. The premises shade parts of the M circle, but they do not shade all of S outside P. In particular, the S-only region is left open. The conclusion claims that all S are P, but the premise diagram does not show that.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Invalid.</em> This has two particular premises. One X is in M outside P, and the other is in S and M. Neither X is forced into the S-and-not-P region. The X marks could refer to different things, and neither one is committed to the region needed by the conclusion.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Invalid.</em> This also has two particular premises. The first X is somewhere in P-and-M, and the second is somewhere in S-and-M. Nothing forces either X into S-and-P, and the two X marks need not represent the same object. The conclusion's I claim is not shown.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch7-exercise-set-6-mixed-review">
    <title>Chapter 7, Exercise Set 6: Mixed Review</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> S = people calling for slower deployment; P = accelerationists; M = AI safety researchers.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: No AI safety researchers are accelerationists.</p>
    <p>P2: All people calling for slower deployment are AI safety researchers.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: No people calling for slower deployment are accelerationists.</p>
    <p>This is EAE-1, so it is valid.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> S = eligible citizens; P = people who returned a ballot; M = non-voters.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: No non-voters are people who returned a ballot.</p>
    <p>P2: Some eligible citizens are non-voters.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Some eligible citizens are not people who returned a ballot.</p>
    <p>This is EIO-1, so it is valid.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> S = records produced by the council; P = public documents; M = committee reports.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: Some committee reports are not public documents.</p>
    <p>P2: All committee reports are records produced by the council.</p>
    <p>Therefore C: Some records produced by the council are not public documents.</p>
    <p>This is OAO-3, so it is valid. The O premise places an X in M outside P; the A premise rules out the part of M outside S, forcing that X into S outside P.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch8-exercise-set-1-simple-and-compound-statements">
    <title>Chapter 8, Exercise Set 1: Simple and Compound Statements</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Simple. For purposes of sentential logic, this is one atomic statement.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Compound. The main connective in English is the conditional: <q>if ... then.</q></p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Compound. The main connective in English is negation: <q>did not.</q></p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch8-exercise-set-2-symbolizing-single-statements">
    <title>Chapter 8, Exercise Set 2: Symbolizing Single Statements</title>
    <p>Using the provided key: <m>P</m> = the proposal passes; <m>Q</m> = the mayor signs the proposal; <m>R</m> = the policy takes effect.</p>
    <p><term>1.</term> <m>P \cdot Q</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <m>P \supset R</m>.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <m>P \equiv Q</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch8-exercise-set-3-main-connective-and-scope">
    <title>Chapter 8, Exercise Set 3: Main Connective and Scope</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Main connective: <m>\supset</m>. Immediate components: <m>(P \cdot Q)</m> and <m>R</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Main connective: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m>. Immediate component: <m>(P \lor Q)</m>.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Main connective: <m>\lor</m>. Immediate components: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> and <m>(Q \cdot R)</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch8-exercise-set-4-conditionals-in-english">
    <title>Chapter 8, Exercise Set 4: Conditionals in English</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Let <m>A</m> = the alarm sounds. Let <m>B</m> = the building will be evacuated. Symbolization: <m>A \supset B</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Let <m>A</m> = the alarm sounds. Let <m>B</m> = the building will be evacuated. Symbolization: <m>B \supset A</m>. The phrase <q>only if</q> points to the necessary condition.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Let <m>D</m> = the judge grants a delay. Let <m>H</m> = the hearing will proceed. Minimal symbolization: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}D \supset H</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch8-exercise-set-5-symbolizing-arguments">
    <title>Chapter 8, Exercise Set 5: Symbolizing Arguments</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Let <m>S</m> = the storm reaches campus before noon. Let <m>L</m> = afternoon labs will be canceled.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: <m>S \supset L</m></p>
    <p>P2: <m>S</m></p>
    <p>Therefore C: <m>L</m></p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Let <m>P</m> = the proposal cleared committee. Let <m>T</m> = the chair tabled the proposal.</p>
    <p>Standard form:</p>
    <p>P1: <m>P \lor T</m></p>
    <p>P2: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></p>
    <p>Therefore C: <m>T</m></p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch8-exercise-set-6-mixed-translation">
    <title>Chapter 8, Exercise Set 6: Mixed Translation</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Let <m>A</m> = the council will approve the budget. Let <m>R</m> = the revenue forecast improves. Let <m>H</m> = the public hearing goes smoothly. Symbolization: <m>A \supset (R \cdot H)</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Let <m>M</m> = the committee met. Let <m>P</m> = the proposal advanced. Symbolization: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(M \cdot P)</m>.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Let <m>R</m> = the server is repaired. Let <m>O</m> = the site will stay offline. Let <m>D</m> = students will miss the deadline. Minimal symbolization: <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R \supset (O \cdot D)</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch9-exercise-set-1-basic-truth-tables">
    <title>Chapter 9, Exercise Set 1: Basic Truth Tables</title>
    <p>Truth values are listed in the standard row order. For one letter: T, F. For two letters: TT, TF, FT, FF.</p>
    <p><term>1.</term> <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>: F, T.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <m>P \lor Q</m>: T, T, T, F.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <m>P \equiv Q</m>: T, F, F, T.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch9-exercise-set-2-well-formed-formulas">
    <title>Chapter 9, Exercise Set 2: Well-Formed Formulas</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Well formed. <m>(P \cdot Q)</m> combines two sentence letters with a binary connective and has the required parentheses.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Not well formed. <m>P \cdot \lor Q</m> places two binary connectives together, so <m>\cdot</m> does not have a complete formula on its right and <m>\lor</m> does not have a complete formula on its left.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Not well formed. <m>(P \supset Q</m> is missing the closing parenthesis.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch9-exercise-set-3-order-of-operations">
    <title>Chapter 9, Exercise Set 3: Order of Operations</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> In <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m>, complete <m>\cdot</m> first and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m> second.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> In <m>(P \lor Q) \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m>, complete <m>\lor</m> first, <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m> second, and the main <m>\cdot</m> third.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch9-exercise-set-4-classifying-statements">
    <title>Chapter 9, Exercise Set 4: Classifying Statements</title>
    <p>Truth values are values under the main operator in the standard row order.</p>
    <p><term>1.</term> <m>P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>: T, T. This is a tautology.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <m>P \supset Q</m>: T, F, T, T. This is contingent.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m>: F, F, F, T. This is contingent.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch9-exercise-set-5-comparing-pairs">
    <title>Chapter 9, Exercise Set 5: Comparing Pairs</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor Q</m> are logically equivalent. Both have main-operator values T, F, T, T.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <m>P</m> and <m>P \lor Q</m> are consistent but not equivalent. They are both true on the TT and TF rows, but they differ on the FT row.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch9-exercise-set-6-testing-arguments">
    <title>Chapter 9, Exercise Set 6: Testing Arguments</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Valid. There is no row where <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>P</m> are both true while <m>Q</m> is false.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Valid. There is no row where <m>P \lor Q</m> and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> are both true while <m>Q</m> is false.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch10-exercise-set-1-identifying-rules">
    <title>Chapter 10, Exercise Set 1: Identifying Rules</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Modus Ponens (MP).</em> The first given line has the form <m>P \supset Q</m>, and the second given line affirms the antecedent, <m>P</m>. Modus Ponens permits us to infer the consequent, <m>Q</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Simplification (Simp).</em> The given line is the conjunction <m>P \cdot Q</m>. Simplification permits us to infer either conjunct from a conjunction, so it permits the inference to <m>Q</m>.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Hypothetical Syllogism (HS).</em> The two given lines are conditionals that chain together: <m>P \supset Q</m> takes us from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>, and <m>Q \supset R</m> takes us from <m>Q</m> to <m>R</m>. Hypothetical Syllogism permits the direct conditional <m>P \supset R</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch10-exercise-set-2-supply-the-missing-line">
    <title>Chapter 10, Exercise Set 2: Supply the Missing Line</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> The missing line is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,2 MP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Line 1 is a conditional, and line 2 gives its antecedent. By Modus Ponens, the consequent <m>Q</m> follows on line 3.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> The missing line is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \lor R</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>1 Simp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P \lor R</m></cell><cell>2 Add</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Line 2 already extracts <m>P</m> from the conjunction on line 1. Addition then permits us to infer <m>P \lor R</m> from <m>P</m>, because if <m>P</m> is true, the disjunction <m>P \lor R</m> is true regardless of whether <m>R</m> is true.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch10-exercise-set-3-short-proofs">
    <title>Chapter 10, Exercise Set 3: Short Proofs</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>Q \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset R</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell><cell>1,2 HS</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>The two premises form a conditional chain. Line 1 says that <m>P</m> leads to <m>Q</m>, and line 2 says that <m>Q</m> leads to <m>R</m>. Hypothetical Syllogism licenses the direct route from <m>P</m> to <m>R</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \lor R</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>1,2 DS</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>P \lor R</m></cell><cell>3 Add</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Line 1 says that either <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> is true. Line 2 rules out <m>Q</m>, so Disjunctive Syllogism gives <m>P</m> on line 3. Once <m>P</m> is available, Addition gives the target disjunction <m>P \lor R</m>.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \lor R) \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \cdot S</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>2 Simp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>P \lor R</m></cell><cell>3 Add</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>S</m></cell><cell>1,4 MP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot S</m></cell><cell>3,5 Conj</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>The target is a conjunction, so we need both <m>P</m> and <m>S</m>. Line 2 gives <m>P</m> by Simplification. From <m>P</m>, Addition gives <m>P \lor R</m>, which is the antecedent needed for line 1. Modus Ponens then gives <m>S</m>. Finally, Conjunction joins the available <m>P</m> and <m>S</m> into the target <m>P \cdot S</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch10-exercise-set-4-explain-the-strategy">
    <title>Chapter 10, Exercise Set 4: Explain the Strategy</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Since the target is <m>P \cdot Q</m>, I would try to use Conjunction as the final rule. Conjunction requires both conjuncts separately, so the proof strategy is to derive or locate <m>P</m> on one line and <m>Q</m> on another line, then cite those two lines with Conj to get <m>P \cdot Q</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Since the target is <m>Q \lor S</m> and <m>Q</m> is already available, I would use Addition. Addition allows us to infer a disjunction from either one of its disjuncts, so from <m>Q</m> alone we may infer <m>Q \lor S</m>. We do not need to prove <m>S</m> separately.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch11-exercise-set-1-identifying-replacement-rules">
    <title>Chapter 11, Exercise Set 1: Identifying Replacement Rules</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>De Morgan's Theorems (DeM).</em> A negated conjunction is rewritten as a disjunction of negations.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Transposition (Trans).</em> A conditional is rewritten as its contrapositive: the antecedent and consequent swap positions and each is negated.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Commutation (Com).</em> The order of the disjuncts is swapped. Com applies to disjunctions and conjunctions, not to conditionals.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> <em>De Morgan's Theorems (DeM).</em> A negated disjunction is rewritten as a conjunction of negations. (This is the second form of DeM.)</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch11-exercise-set-2-apply-the-rule">
    <title>Chapter 11, Exercise Set 2: Apply the Rule</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> DeM applied to <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(R \lor S)</m> gives <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m>. The negation distributes and the disjunction becomes a conjunction.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Trans applied to <m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m> gives <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, which simplifies by DN to <m>Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. (Either form is acceptable; the Trans step itself produces the double-negated version.)</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Dist applied to <m>P \cdot (Q \lor R)</m> gives <m>(P \cdot Q) \lor (P \cdot R)</m>. The conjunction distributes across the disjunction.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> Exp applied to <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m> gives <m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m>. The conjoined antecedent is separated into two nested conditionals.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch11-exercise-set-3-proofs-using-replacement-rules">
    <title>Chapter 11, Exercise Set 3: Proofs Using Replacement Rules</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>1 DeM</cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>2 Simp</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>De Morgan's breaks the negated disjunction into a conjunction of negations. Simplification extracts the first conjunct.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>R</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell>1 Exp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>R</m></cell><cell>2,3 MP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Exportation rewrites the nested conditional so that the conjunction <m>P \cdot Q</m> is the antecedent. MP with line 2 finishes the proof.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \equiv Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>(P \supset Q) \cdot (Q \supset P)</m></cell><cell>1 Equiv</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell>3 Simp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>2,4 MP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Material Equivalence unpacks the biconditional into two conditionals. Simplification extracts the one we need, and MP finishes.</p>
    <p><term>7.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \lor Q)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>1 DeM</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>3 Simp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>2,4 MT</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>DeM breaks line 1 open. Simplification gives <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. Since <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> is the negation of the consequent of line 2, Modus Tollens gives <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch11-exercise-set-4-explain-the-strategy">
    <title>Chapter 11, Exercise Set 4: Explain the Strategy</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> I would use De Morgan's Theorems. <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m> is a negated conjunction, and De Morgan's rewrites it as <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m> in one step. The trigger pattern is a tilde in front of parentheses containing a conjunction.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> I would use Transposition. Trans rewrites <m>P \supset Q</m> as <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, which is exactly the contrapositive needed for the HS chain. The trigger is needing a conditional with swapped and negated terms.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> I would use Exportation. Exp rewrites <m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m> as <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m>. Since <m>P \cdot Q</m> is already available, MP can then fire directly to give <m>R</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch12-exercise-set-1-identify-the-strategy">
    <title>Chapter 12, Exercise Set 1: Identify the Strategy</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Conditional Proof.</em> The target is a conditional (<m>P \supset Q</m>), so assume the antecedent <m>P</m> and try to derive the consequent <m>Q</m> inside the scope.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Direct proof.</em> The premises <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>Q \supset R</m> chain together by Hypothetical Syllogism to give <m>P \supset R</m> in one step. No assumption is needed.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Conditional Proof.</em> The target <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m> is a conditional, so assume the antecedent <m>P \cdot Q</m> and try to derive <m>R</m> inside the scope.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch12-exercise-set-2-complete-the-cp-proof">
    <title>Chapter 12, Exercise Set 2: Complete the CP Proof</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Completed proof:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>Q \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset R</m></cell></row>

      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,3 MP</cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R</m></cell><cell>2,4 MP</cell></row>

      <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell><cell>3–5 CP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p><term>3.</term> Completed proof:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset S</m></cell><cell>/ <m>(P \cdot R) \supset (Q \cdot S)</m></cell></row>

      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P \cdot R</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>3 Simp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R</m></cell><cell>3 Simp</cell></row>
      <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,4 MP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>S</m></cell><cell>2,5 MP</cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>8.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q \cdot S</m></cell><cell>6,7 Conj</cell></row>

      <row><cell>9.</cell><cell><m>(P \cdot R) \supset (Q \cdot S)</m></cell><cell>3–8 CP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch12-exercise-set-3-complete-the-ip-proof">
    <title>Chapter 12, Exercise Set 3: Complete the IP Proof</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Completed proof:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P</m></cell></row>

      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,3 MP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>2,3 MP</cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>4,5 Conj</cell></row>

      <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>3–6 IP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>8.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>7 DN</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p><term>3.</term> Completed proof:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \lor Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>

      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P \lor Q</m></cell><cell>3 Add</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R</m></cell><cell>1,4 MP</cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>5,2 Conj</cell></row>

      <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>3–6 IP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Note that the target is <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, so we assume <m>P</m> (the opposite). IP gives <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> directly — no DN needed because the assumption was not negated.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch12-exercise-set-4-full-proofs">
    <title>Chapter 12, Exercise Set 4: Full Proofs</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset (Q \cdot R)</m></cell></row>

      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,3 MP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R</m></cell><cell>2,3 MP</cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q \cdot R</m></cell><cell>4,5 Conj</cell></row>

      <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \cdot R)</m></cell><cell>3–6 CP</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>The target is a conditional, so CP is the natural strategy. Assume <m>P</m>, derive both <m>Q</m> and <m>R</m> by MP, and Conj gives the consequent.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>

      <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>1,3 MT</cell></row>
      <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>2,4 MP</cell></row>
      <row bottom="minor"><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>5,3 Conj</cell></row>

      <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>3–6 IP</cell></row>
      <row><cell>8.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>7 DN</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>The target is not a conditional, and <m>Q</m> cannot be derived directly. Assume <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>. MT with line 1 gives <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. MP with line 2 gives <m>Q</m> — which contradicts the assumption. Build the explicit contradiction, discharge, and DN to finish.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> A complete proof is:</p>
    <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
      <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell></row>
      <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell>1 Exp</cell></row>
    </tabular>
    <p>Exportation handles this in one step. Alternatively, a CP proof works: assume <m>P \cdot Q</m>, simplify to get <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, MP twice, and discharge. But Exp is shorter.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch13-exercise-set-1-deductive-or-inductive">
    <title>Chapter 13, Exercise Set 1: Deductive or Inductive?</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Deductive.</em> The argument has the form: all biology majors must complete the requirement; Ana is a biology major; therefore Ana must complete the requirement. If the premises are true, the conclusion follows necessarily.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Deductive.</em> This is modus ponens: if the server is down, the login page will not load; the server is down; therefore the login page will not load. The premises are intended to guarantee the conclusion.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Deductive.</em> The premise says no committee members voted against the proposal. Since Lee is a committee member, Lee is included in that group. The conclusion follows with certainty if the premises are true.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch13-exercise-set-2-strong-or-weak">
    <title>Chapter 13, Exercise Set 2: Strong or Weak?</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Weak.</em> One person's opinion in the dining hall is too small and too informal a sample to support a conclusion about students generally. The main problem is sample size and representativeness.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Moderate, but not strong.</em> Three previous assignments give some evidence of a pattern, but the sample is small and course schedules can change. The evidence supports the conclusion only modestly.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Weak.</em> The first five commenters are a tiny, self-selected sample. Angry readers are more likely to comment, and <q>everyone who read the article</q> is a much broader population than the observed comments.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch13-exercise-set-3-samples-and-generalizations">
    <title>Chapter 13, Exercise Set 3: Samples and Generalizations</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Sample: ten friends in the student's residence hall. Population: UMW students. Possible problem: the sample is small, local, and socially connected to the person asking, so it may not represent commuters, upper-class students, or students with different parking needs.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Sample: five negative comments the host read. Population: the movie's audience, or potential audience, as a whole. Possible problem: comments are self-selected and negative reactions are often overrepresented; five comments are not enough to support a broad claim about audience opinion.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch13-exercise-set-4-causal-reasoning">
    <title>Chapter 13, Exercise Set 4: Causal Reasoning</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> One alternative explanation is that more motivated or better-prepared students choose seats near the front. Another is that students who attend consistently also tend to sit near the front. The seating location may be correlated with habits that affect grades rather than causing the grades directly.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Possible alternative explanations include better safety education, fewer cyclists downtown, changes in traffic enforcement, weather patterns, or changes in accident reporting. The timing is suggestive, but the decrease alone does not prove that the bike lanes caused it.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch13-exercise-set-5-analogy-and-explanation">
    <title>Chapter 13, Exercise Set 5: Analogy and Explanation</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Argument by analogy.</em> The current course is being compared with a previous course. The analogy is reasonably relevant because textbook, quiz format, and instructor can all affect study strategy, though it would be stronger if the course level, assignments, and student's schedule were also similar.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Argument by analogy, weak.</em> Color and size are usually not relevant to battery life. The argument would be stronger if the two phones had the same model, battery capacity, age, software, and usage pattern.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch13-writing-prompt">
    <title>Chapter 13, Writing Prompt</title>
    <p>No solutions provided. This is an open-ended writing prompt; responses will vary by student.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch14-exercise-set-1-basic-rules">
    <title>Chapter 14, Exercise Set 1: Basic rules</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> There are two equally likely outcomes, heads and tails. So P(tails) = <m>1/2</m>, or 0.5.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> There are four 2s and four 3s in a standard deck, with no overlap. So P(2 or 3) = <m>8/52 = 2/13</m>.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Use the complement rule. P(not declared) = <m>1 - 0.78 = 0.22</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch14-exercise-set-2-conditional-probability">
    <title>Chapter 14, Exercise Set 2: Conditional probability</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Given that the outcome is odd, the possible outcomes are 1, 3, and 5. One of those three outcomes is 3, so the probability is <m>1/3</m>.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Use the multiplication rule. P(first red and second blue) = <m>(5/12)(7/11) = 35/132</m>, approximately 0.265.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> Use the complement. The only way to get no tails is HHH, with probability <m>(1/2)^3 = 1/8</m>. So P(at least one tail) = <m>1 - 1/8 = 7/8</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch14-exercise-set-3-independence">
    <title>Chapter 14, Exercise Set 3: Independence</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> <em>Independent.</em> For fair coin flips, the result of one flip does not change the probability of the next flip. P(heads on the second flip | heads on the first flip) is still 0.5.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> <em>Not plausibly independent.</em> Rain could affect whether students come to class, arrive late, or stay home. Knowing that it rains may change the probability of lower-than-usual attendance.</p>
    <p><term>5.</term> <em>Not independent.</em> Because the cards are drawn without replacement, the first card changes the deck. If the first card is a heart, then the probability that the second card is a heart becomes <m>12/51</m>, not <m>13/52</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch14-exercise-set-4-direction-of-conditioning">
    <title>Chapter 14, Exercise Set 4: Direction of conditioning</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> These are likely very different. P(left-handed | professional baseball pitcher) may be noticeably higher than the left-handed rate in the general population, but P(professional baseball pitcher | left-handed) is tiny because very few left-handed people are professional pitchers.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> These are likely very different. If someone has the flu, a fever is fairly likely. But if someone has a fever, the flu is only one possible explanation among many, so P(has the flu | has a fever) may be much lower.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sol-ch14-exercise-set-5-bayes-theorem-and-base-rates">
    <title>Chapter 14, Exercise Set 5: Bayes' theorem and base rates</title>
    <p><term>1.</term> Let <em>H</em> = the person has the condition and <em>E</em> = the person tests positive. P(<em>H</em>) = <m>1/500 = 0.002</m>, P(<m>{\sim}H</m>) = 0.998, P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) = 0.98, and P(<em>E</em> | <m>{\sim}H</m>) = 0.02. Bayes' theorem gives:</p>
    <p><m>P(H \mid E) = \dfrac{0.98 \cdot 0.002}{(0.98 \cdot 0.002) + (0.02 \cdot 0.998)} = \dfrac{0.00196}{0.02192} \approx 0.089.</m></p>
    <p>So the probability is about 9 percent. The test is good, but the condition is rare enough that false positives still dominate the positive results.</p>
    <p><term>3.</term> Let <em>H</em> = the student fails at least one course and <em>E</em> = the student has bottom-quartile study habits. The study gives P(<em>E</em> | <em>H</em>) = 0.90, not P(<em>H</em> | <em>E</em>). To know the probability that this student will fail, we would also need the base rate of first-semester course failure and the rate of bottom-quartile study habits among students who do not fail. Without those, the conclusion may be a case of confusing the direction of conditioning.</p>
  </section>

